To eliminate arrays in JavaScript that contain identical digit combinations, regardless of their arrangement, we can utilize the `Set` data structure to store unique combinations. Here's how you can achieve this:

Firstly, create a function that takes an array as input and generates all possible permutations of its elements using the `Array.prototype.sort()` method and the `Array.prototype.join()` method. This will allow us to treat each combination as a string and check for uniqueness.

Next, use the `Set` object to store these unique combinations. Since `Set` only stores unique values, any duplicate combinations will automatically be filtered out.

Finally, return the set of unique combinations, which can be converted back into an array using the `Array.from()` method. This will give us the desired result - an array containing unique digit combinations.

Here's a sample code snippet demonstrating this approach:

```javascript
function removeDuplicates(arr) {
  const set = new Set();
  const perms = permute(arr);

  for (let i = 0; i < perms.length; i++) {
    const perm = perms[i].join('');
    set.add(perm);
  }

  return Array.from(set);
}

// Helper function to generate permutations
function permute(arr) {
  if (arr.length === 1) return [arr];

  const result = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    const rest = [...arr.slice(0, i),...arr.slice(i + 1)];
    const p = permute(rest);

    for (let j = 0; j < p.length; j++) {
      result.push([arr[i],...p[j]]);
    }
  }

  return result.map(p => p.sort((a, b) => a - b));
}
```

This solution has a time complexity of O(n!), where n is the length of the input array, due to the generation of all permutations. However, it efficiently eliminates duplicates by utilizing the `Set` data structure, resulting in a space complexity of O(n!). Note that this approach assumes that the input array contains only integers. If the array contains other types of elements, modifications may be necessary.

